{"id":"1407.6381","submitter":"Gabriel Di Lemos Santiago Lima","authors":"Gabriel Di Lemos Santiago Lima","title":"The Relation Between Gauge and Non-Gauge Abelian Models","comments":"20 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This work studies the relationship between gauge-invariant and non\ngauge-invariant abelian vector models. Following a technique introduced by\nHarada and Tsutsui, we show that the Proca and the Chiral Schwinger models may\nboth be viewed as gauge-fixed versions of genuinely gauge- invariant models.\nThis leads to the proposal that any consistent Abelian vector model with no\ngauge symmetry can be understood as a gauge theory that had its gauge fixed,\nwhich establishes an equivalence between gauge-invariant and non\ngauge-invariant models. Finally, we show that a gauge-invariant version of the\nchiral Schwinger model, after integrating out the fermionic degrees of freedom,\ncan be identified with the two-dimensional Stueckelberg model without the gauge\nfixing term.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Jul 2014 06:25:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-07-25"}
{"id":"1407.6681","submitter":"Sam Tarzi","authors":"Sam Tarzi","title":"Multicoloured Random Graphs: The Random Dynamics Program","comments":"This is intended as the third of 3 documents","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Random Dynamics program is a proposal to explain the origin of all\nsymmetries, including Lorentz and gauge invariance without appeal to any\nfundamental invariance of the laws of nature, and to derive the known physical\nlaws in such a way as to be almost unavoidable. C. D. Froggatt and H. B.\nNielsen proposed in their book Origin of Symmetries, that symmetries and\nphysical laws should arise naturally from some essentially random dynamics\nrather than being postulated to be exact. The most useful assumption of the\nprogram that can be made about the fundamental laws is taken to be that they\nare random and then to see how known physics like mechanics and relativity\nfollow from them. It is believed that almost any model of these regularities\nwould appear in some limit for example as energies become small. Almost all\ntheories or models at the fundamental level could then explain known physics.\n  We suggest how using the formalism and properties of random graphs might be\nuseful in developing the theory, and point towards directions in which it can\nbe more fully extended in future work.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Jul 2014 21:24:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-07-25"}
{"id":"1407.7438","submitter":"Carlos  Meriles Prof","authors":"Carlos A. Meriles, Marcus W. Doherty","title":"Generation of spin-polarized currents via cross-relaxation with\n  dynamically pumped paramagnetic impurities","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Applied Physics Letters, 2014","doi":"10.1063/1.4890096","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Key to future spintronics and spin-based information processing technologies\nis the generation, manipulation, and detection of spin polarization in a solid\nstate platform. Here, we theoretically explore an alternative route to spin\ninjection via the use of dynamically polarized nitrogen-vacancy (NV) centers in\ndiamond. We focus on the geometry where carriers and NV centers are confined to\nproximate, parallel layers and use a 'trap-and-release' model to calculate the\nspin cross-relaxation probabilities between the charge carriers and neighboring\nNV centers. We identify near-unity regimes of carrier polarization depending on\nthe NV spin state, applied magnetic field, and carrier g-factor. In particular,\nwe find that unlike holes, electron spins are distinctively robust against\nspin-lattice relaxation by other, unpolarized paramagnetic centers. Further,\nthe polarization process is only weakly dependent on the carrier hopping\ndynamics, which makes this approach potentially applicable over a broad range\nof temperatures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Jul 2014 17:12:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-07-29"}
